description.text:
Hi everyone! I was tired of having my videogames strategically positioned on my shelf so they didnt fall to the side. So I decided to make something like a bookend, but for my videogames.

Its printed in PLA. No support material and with a 0.2 high layer. Because its going to be used to hold videogames and not books, there's no need to make it heavy so you can print it with an infill enough to make it as resistant as you need. I printed this one with a 15% infill. I also added some other model with the famous console shapes (triangle, square, circle and cross).

Be free to print it in different colors and don't be shy to comment or suggest new applications or improvements.

If you liked the design or it was usefull please hit the like button so more people can discover this too!

title: Maze Cylinder Box - Visible and Hidden Versions

description.text:
Another maze box. Inspired by the other great maze and labyrinth boxes on thingiverse.
Features:
. Hidden option so the maze is on the interior of the outside cylinder, making it completely hidden until the entire maze is solved!
. Completely customizable in openscad. The maze is specified by an array. Box sizes and thicknesses are parameters that can be changed. The number of "maze nubs" can be changed.
. Has 6 round protrusions on the bottoms of each cylinder to make them easier to manipulate.
Rel2: fixed bugs in customizable scad files.  In Rel1 the mazes were only correct if nNubs=3.

You can just print the STLs as is.
If you want to customize your maze box, open up the .scad files and read the included instructions there. Render mazeInside() and mazeOutside() to get a complete maze box. You can also render testNubRing() to produce a single ring with the maze nubs that you can print to test your maze without having to print the entire part with the nubs. This allows you to finetune your tolerances before printing the entire part with only the nubs.

description.text: This is Alby, a little humanoid robot designed for makers and enthusiasts. The robot has a CPU based on the Raspberry Pi 3, allowing access to a wide variety of projects from a large community. Alby is equipped with a webcam, OLED displays for its eyes, hobby 9g servomotors for its joints, and DC motors with quadrature encoders for its wheels. The lower level control is handled by an Arduino Pro Mini and a battery LiFe 3S 2200mAh ensures upwards from 2h of continuous operation.

  • 2 units of 210 RPM DC motors with encoder
  • 9 units 9g hobby micro servo motors
  • 16GB micro SD card
  • 1/10 scale RC truck tires (PS.: the tires come as a set with the DC motors above)
  • Battery 2200mAh 3S LiFe

  • Cables and connectors

description.text: An adapter to allow a GoPro Hero camera to be used in a UoPlay smartphone gimbal in horizontal (fully controllable) mode.

Notes:

This is one of the things I bought a 3D printer to do. The UoPlay gimbal is designed for phones, but with this adapter you can use it to hold a GoPro Hero camera. The camera is a nice push fit on my print but you could always just wrap a rubber band around it if yours is a little looser.

You will need the extra counterweight on the right - as you would for a larger or heavier phone - but with that in place, the whole outfit balances perfectly. The only downside is that you will not be able to use the widest angle setting on the GoPro as the motor will be caught in frame on the right.

There are cutouts for the shutter button (so pushing in the camera does not start recording) the microphone so the camera can still hear and for the sockets on the side. You can always adjust the .stl file to move, blank off, widen anything for any other GoPro or similar models - I only have a Hero 4 so this was designed for that.

title: Filter mount Yukon Spartan NVMT 1x24 Gen 1 Night Vision Device

description.text:
This is a mounting ring to mount a filter to a Yukon Spartan Gen 1 Night vision device. It doesn't have a threading. You just push it into the objective and it should sit tight enough to stay there even with heavy use. The filter material has to be glued to the outer ring. This works well with infrared tranparent plastic or dark but transparent plastic. Camera filters are neither necessary nor useful because optical quality isn't needed with a gen 1 tube and those filters are to brittle for a night vision device. The inner ring is slightly bigger than the inner diameter of the rubber of the objective of the tube and does not interfere with focusing. It can be sanded smaller to fit into the objective if necessary. This device has 3 uses:

  • Use the gen 1 tube during the day with a dark/black filter to "emulate" a gen 3 tube at lower price while using ambient light instead of an infrared illuminator. This way you have a greater range than with an infrared illuminator and almost the same user experience as if using an expensive gen 2 or gen 3 tube.

  • Mount an infrared filter to the night vision device. This reduces glare and visual distractions through artificial light sources like cities, cars or flash lights a bit.

  • Screw a cap on the infrared illuminator and use the device together with an eye cap and a head mount during the day for airsoft or paintball in Germany without having the problem of using an illegal "target illuminating device" and without the need to buy/risk an expensive gen 3 tube for sporting purposes.
    • A night vision device does not count as eye protection. Softairs and paintballs can get you blind and knock out your teeth.

The filter film goes between the two rings. If you don't print out the second one it will get scratched soon. Stuff that works as a fitler includes window tinting film, acrylic glas or old photografic film.

I first measured and CAD the 2 pin connector header in CATIA, surprisingly it fitted like it was born to be in first try. Then i designed the base for the header, spliced an existing phone cable and exposed only the VCC and ground wire. I fed the wires with the plastic shield through the header base, then tied a knot on the plastic shield for strain relief. Inserted the VCC and ground into their corresponding pin hole and superglued the base to the header.

voila, works like a charm.
